This is quite a simple problem, however often definitions change and rules get added. So in order to account for future changes we need to design a solution that is simple to extend should the need arise.
To accomplish this we use a bitmask to hold different properties and we can then determine the category by querying the bits which are referenced using an enum. The individual bits of the mask can be set using the `xor` or `or` operations using the appropriate `Category`.
If for whatever reason that the state couldn't be represented with 64 bits, then we could move to a bitset and change the enum from powers of 2 to indexes into the bitset.
```
class Solution {
public:
    string categorizeBox(int length, int width, int height, int mass) {
	  // define the underlying type of the bitmask, in case we need to extend the size due to added categories
      using utype = unsigned char;
      enum Category { //Define the different categories (using powers of 2, next category would be 4)
        None  = 0,
        Bulky = 1,
        Heavy = 2,
      };
      utype mask = 0;

      // Apply the category rules to determine the state of the bitmask
      if ((length >= 1e4) || (width >= 1e4) || (height >= 1e4) 
          || (long long) length * width * height >= 1e9) // Don't overflow integers as volume can be upto 1e15
        mask ^= Bulky;
      if (mass >= 100)
        mask ^= Heavy;

	  // Query state to determine which categories apply
      switch(mask) {
        case Bulky: 
          return "Bulky";
        case Heavy: 
          return "Heavy";
        case Bulky | Heavy: 
          return "Both";
      }

      return "Neither";
    }
};
```

