# Intuition
The problem requires categorizing a box based on its dimensions (length, width, height) and mass. The categories are "Both" (if the box is both bulky and heavy), "Bulky" (if the box is bulky but not heavy), "Heavy" (if the box is heavy but not bulky), and "Neither" (if the box is neither bulky nor heavy).

# Approach
The given code already provides a straightforward approach to solving the problem. It calculates the volume of the box by multiplying its length, width, and height (vol = length * width * height). It also checks if any of the dimensions (length, width, height) is greater than or equal to 10^4 (dim = height >= 10 ** 4 || length >= 10 ** 4 || width >= 10 ** 4).

The code then determines whether the box is bulky (isBulky) based on the calculated volume (vol >= 10 ** 9) or if any dimension is greater than or equal to 10^4. Similarly, it determines whether the box is heavy (isHeavy) based on the given mass (mass >= 100).

Finally, the code uses conditional statements to return the appropriate category based on the values of isBulky and isHeavy.

# Complexity
* Time complexity: O(1) - The code performs a constant number of operations to calculate the volume, check the dimensions, and compare the mass. Regardless of the input values, the time complexity remains constant.
* Space complexity: O(1) - The code uses a constant amount of space to store the calculated volume (vol) and the dimensions check (dim). The space complexity does not depend on the input size.

